    <body><div type="letter">
      <p>Wednesday. 1 o'clock</p>
      <p>Dearest W. Out of the question today to set upon even dear Tag-Rag's 4 legs, &amp; he buffetted by the savage wind of the moors, in the centre of such a collection of it as one's habit would take in. But I am glad to have had my horse over too.</p>
      <p>The 2 enclosed are to me agreeable; tho' in Charlotte's I still perceive a tone of</p>
      <p>selfishness that I dislike.</p>
      <p>However, as you observed very justly, it is doubtless to them a great break-up &amp; change.--</p>
      <p>Mrs H-- says that Sir G. is very handsome &amp; attractive; (&amp; in person not at all too big, or what exceeds the proportions of a fine well-made man); in general company silent &amp; uncommunicative, with much in him when aroused in particular conversation.</p>
      <p>Halliday was at Eaton with him. Both he &amp; Mrs</p>
      <p>H-- seem to think highly of him, &amp; warmly congratulate me on H's prospect as his wife.</p>
      <p>I am as happy as possible, &amp; in great spirits. I have read a quantity of Dickens' American Notes, which would delight even you.</p>
      <p>There is such elegance &amp; refinement in all his jokes; such real wit; such original ideas &amp; comparisons; &amp; such profound remarks; &amp; always kindly &amp; high moral tone; that he cannot but</p>
      <p>captivate the impartial I think in this work.</p>
      <p>We are just going to set out for Fairyland &amp;c. So I must conclude.</p>
      <p>I find myself so much better &amp; refreshed by being here; that if I should tomorrow feel I like to remain a night longer, I am sure you will not object. But if so, I shall send over tomorrow I suppose probably. I think even my music would not perhaps lose; and the Hallidays so suit me (which no one scarcely you know does).</p>
    </div></body>
